{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 13:33:29.154492", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnostic report — multi-tier Clos EBGP lab\n\nSummary\n- Control plane (BGP) is healthy: all routers have established EBGP sessions and the leaf /24 host networks are being advertised and learned across the fabric.\n- Observed data-plane anomaly localized to host configuration(s): pc_0_1 is misconfigured with the wrong IP and default gateway and is using the same IP as pc_0_0. This causes address duplication and makes 10.0.1.2 unreachable from pc_0_0 (the destination host does not exist on the subnet as configured).\n\nKey findings (evidence + interpretation)\n\n1) Host addressing mismatch / duplication (primary anomaly)\n- pc_0_0 ip addr:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24\n  - route: default via 10.0.0.1\n- pc_0_1 ip addr:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24\n  - route: default via 10.0.0.1\n- leaf_router_0_0 (serving pc_0_0) has eth2 = 10.0.0.1/24; leaf_router_0_1 (serving pc_0_1) has eth2 = 10.0.1.1/24.\n\nInterpretation:\n- pc_0_1 should be in 10.0.1.0/24 (e.g., 10.0.1.2) with default gateway 10.0.1.1 (leaf_router_0_1). Instead pc_0_1 is configured as 10.0.0.2 with gateway 10.0.0.1 — identical to pc_0_0. This is a host-level misconfiguration creating an IP conflict / incorrect subnet for pc_0_1.\n\n2) Demonstrated symptom: ping to 10.0.1.2 fails with ICMP unreachable\n- From pc_0_0: ping -c 4 10.0.1.2\n  - Response: \"From 172.16.0.7 icmp_seq=N Destination Host Unreachable\" for each probe.\n- 172.16.0.7 is the leaf_router_0_1 inter-router address — the router closest to the 10.0.1.0/24 network is returning host-unreachable.\n\nInterpretation:\n- Packets from pc_0_0 traverse the fabric to leaf_router_0_1, which cannot reach (or ARP for) 10.0.1.2 on its directly-connected subnet and therefore returns ICMP Host Unreachable. This aligns with the fact that no host is configured as 10.0.1.2 — pc_0_1 is not on 10.0.1.0/24.\n\n3) Control plane (BGP) status — healthy\n- super_spine_router_0: show ip bgp summary\n  - neighbors 172.16.0.1 (AS65100) and 172.16.0.3 (AS65101) — both up; PfxRcd = 2 each.\n- spine_router_0_0 / spine_router_0_1: BGP neighbors up; table contains routes to 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 (spine routers show multiple paths where expected).\n- leaf_router_0_0 / leaf_router_0_1: BGP neighbors up and each advertises its network:\n  - leaf_router_0_0 BGP: network 10.0.0.0/24\n  - leaf_router_0_1 BGP: network 10.0.1.0/24\n- Routing tables on routers show the two /24s present and selected routes in RIB.\n\nInterpretation:\n- The EBGP topology and route advertisement/propagation are working: control-plane convergence is achieved and routes to the host subnets are present on all routers. There is no evidence of BGP session failures or lost route advertisement.\n\nLocalization (faulty device(s))\n- Host: pc_0_1 — incorrect IP (10.0.0.2 instead of being in 10.0.1.0/24) and incorrect default gateway (10.0.0.1). This host is the primary cause of the observed host-to-host reachability issues.\n- No router was found to have BGP session down or missing route advertisements; routers appear to be functioning correctly.\n\nProbable root cause\n- Human/configuration error on pc_0_1 (host-level misconfiguration): IP address and gateway assigned to pc_0_1 belong to the other pod/leaf (10.0.0.0/24) rather than its intended /24 (10.0.1.0/24). Because no device is assigned 10.0.1.2, attempts to reach 10.0.1.2 correctly result in ARP failure/ICMP Host Unreachable from the leaf router.\n\nImpact\n- Host-to-host connectivity that relies on correct end-host addressing is affected:\n  - pc_0_0 cannot reach 10.0.1.2 (destination doesn’t exist).\n  - Address duplication (two hosts configured with 10.0.0.2) can cause intermittent connectivity problems, ARP flux, or packet delivery ambiguity on 10.0.0.0/24.\n- Control plane (BGP) and inter-router forwarding are not the source of the current problem.\n\nAdditional observations / notes\n- Inter-router link addressing and BGP peering appear consistent: /31 links are present and used, and FRR configs show correct neighbor ASes.\n- The super-spine's route installation shows both /24s via one spine neighbor in its RIB; that is consistent with BGP next-hop selection in this lab but is not related to the host-level symptom.\n- Reachability check run earlier that showed pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0 succeeding is consistent with both hosts being in the same /24 and having identical IPs (pc_0_1 and pc_0_0 were both configured 10.0.0.2); that masks the misconfiguration for ping in that particular direction but does not indicate correct overall addressing.\n\nConclusion\n- Control plane: OK (BGP sessions and route propagation established).\n- Data plane host-level: misconfiguration on pc_0_1 (duplicate/wrong IP and gateway) causing host-unreachable for the intended 10.0.1.0/24 endpoint. The problem is localized to pc_0_1 and its addressing, not to the router fabric.\n\nNo mitigations are provided here per instructions. If you want, I can (on request) list the exact evidence excerpts (command outputs) used to reach these conclusions, or provide further active tests to confirm specific behaviors.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 13745, "output_tokens": 3126, "total_tokens": 16871, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 13568}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1664}}}
